Sub-Sahara Africa Stocks: AccessKenya, East African Breweries

-- B y   C h r i s   K a y
-- 
2011-04-08T11:37:26Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-04-08/sub-sahara-africa-stocks-accesskenya-east-african-breweries.html
Mauritius’s SEMDEX Index gained for
a third day, adding 0.6 percent to 2,029.26 at the 1:30 p.m.
close in  Port Louis , the highest since Feb. 25.  The Ghana Stock Exchange Composite Index fell 0.8 percent
to 1,055.28 at 12:08 p.m. in Accra, heading for a weekly loss of
1.2 percent. Kenya’s All-Share Index added 0.3 percent to 74.48
at 2:08 p.m. in Nairobi, snapping two days of declines. The
Nigerian Stock Exchange All-Share Index advanced for a second
day, gaining 0.6 percent to 24,883.47 by 12:11 p.m. on Lagos,
according to data compiled by Bloomberg. Namibia’s FTSE/ Namibia
Overall Index (FTN098)  rose 0.8 percent to 897.21 by 1:12 p.m. in
Windhoek.  The following shares rose or fell in sub-Saharan  Africa ,
excluding  South Africa . Stock symbols are in parentheses.  AccessKenya (ACCESS)  Group Ltd. (ACCESS KN), the East African
nation’s only publically traded  Internet company , rallied for a
seventh day, its longest winning streak in nine months, climbing
55 cents, or 5.6 percent, to 10.3 shillings, as the company’s
earnings outlook improved, Timothy Wambu, a Nairobi-based
analyst at CFC Stanbic Financial Services Ltd., said by phone
from Nairobi today.  East African Breweries Ltd. (EABL)  , Diageo Plc’s unit in
Kenya, gained for a 10th day, the longest winning streak on
record, adding 5 shillings,  or 2.6 percent, to 200 shillings
after the  Daily Nation  reported the company raised prices on its
products by as much as 10 percent.  To contact the reporter on this story:
Chris Kay in London at 
